<br>
First is that you lose alot of control over your bard using this thing so it's not a good idea when you are pulling etc, I find it most useful for bog boring chant kites....<br>
<br>
The nostromo comes with software to set up key presses and macros to bind to the controller..<br>
<br>
The n52 brought an improvment to the software so I'll cover the old way as well as the new at the end, in terms of looping..<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Open up eq and start placing gems to the hot keys... then bind those song based hotkeys to function keys. keep in mind alt f4 = close eq so avoid f4. =)<br>
<br>
make a hot key that's simple &lt;/stopsong&gt; and bind it to say f5..<br>
<br>
example...<br>
<br>
song 1 f1<br>
song 2 f2 <br>
song 3 f3<br>
song 4 f6<br>
/stopsong f5<br>
<br>
using function keys allows you to run the nostromo and chat. binding the gems to hot keys allows you to change songs whenever you want.<br>
<br>
since you can bind two keys to any one hotkey, you can keep your manual 12345 or whatever as one set and the function keys as another.<br>
<br>
Once the hot key bank is set up... note the bank number if you wish to get fancy.<br>
<br>
the nostromo software allows you to make macros that contain a series of key presses and save them as a free floating macro name which can then be bound to a key<br>
<br>
<br>
a typical macro would be<br>
<br>
press f1<br>
delay .1         {song f1 start - play with the .1 delay}<br>
release f1<br>
<br>
delay 3.2      {main song delay to allow for song to start - allow for lag}<br>
<br>
press f5<br>
delay .1         [single press of /stopsong hot key}<br>
release f5<br>
<br>
Then repeat that for songs 2 3 and maybe 4<br>
<br>
save the macro as say twist3.2x3 so you can tell at a glance 3.2 is the delay on songs and x3 is a three song twist.<br>
<br>
save another where the delay is 3.3 for a 3 song twist for low framerate situations. For a 4 song twist you want to lower the delays to 3.1 or 3.05<br>
<br>
for the fancy pants, use f7 or something to bind to the &quot;Hot Button Page x&quot; at the start where x is the hotkey window you have the stop key at. Press f7 at the start of the macro and that way the macro will automatically hit the right keys.<br>
<br>
<br>
now that you have the macro finished, check either an option to keep the macro repeated.. see below for more info..<br>
<br>
It's then time to bind said macro to a key... choose a key and then pick macro... and choose from the list of macros you have made .<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
the n52 allowed you to check off a box named.... &quot;repeat macro until key is pressed again&quot; This is new and is nice because you can keep several types of macros at the ready. This is bad because once you start a macro there's no indicator WHICH key is running.. the nostromo will gladdly be running 5 different macros at the same time if your cat takes a liking to the pad.<br>
<br>
The old way is to use &quot; repeat macro while key is pressed down&quot; this is awkward in that how do you keep a key down???<br>
<br>
<br>
well let me introduce the dreaded THROTTLE!!! <br>
<br>
the throttle can be used in many different ways but the one I use is the banded mode...<br>
<br>
click on the throttle and click &quot;Define Axis&quot;<br>
<br>
from there check the radio button  &quot; Use Bands&quot; and the window below lightens up.<br>
<br>
you start with 3 bands and those consist of (PHEAR THE ASCII MUHAHAHAHA)<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
....blank<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
......off<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
....blank<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
this means if the throttle is in the middle it's off and if in the top region it does  &quot;blank&quot;<br>
<br>
lets change that... first lets right click on the top band and click &quot;New macro&quot;... choose the macro you just made say  'twist3.2x3' and it will now look like<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
twist3.2x3<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
......off<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
....blank<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
now I just want the throttle to play one twist so it's time to  delete the bottom region... right click on blank's area and near the bottom of the menu, click &quot;Delete Region&quot;<br>
<br>
*poof*<br>
<br>
you now have<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
twist3.2x3<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
<br>
......off<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
 see? that means if the throttle is not at the top, the macro is off.<br>
 lets spiffy that up a bit and limit the active area... <br>
<br>
left click and hold the dividing line and and a up/down arrow icon appears.. drag the bar up to about 90%<br>
<br>
<br>
like....<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
twist3.2x3<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
......off<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
now call it Liqsucks or whatever floats your boat and click ok.<br>
<br>
the box next to the throttle will give the axis name you chose... not the macro inside.<br>
<br>
you can get fancy and make lots of different bands, use more than one twist per bar etc but I'm a firm believer in kiss (keep it simple stupid) when it comes to stuff like this.<br>
<br>
anyway that's how I use nostromo... feel free to experiment.  again try not to use this on raids ok?!<br>
<br>
Cheers!<br>
-notLiq<br>
